Section section_02 (Chars 8346–12732):
Section Summary: The Sarö Yögur people's homes were traditionally furnished with Chinese-style sleeping stoves, Buddhist altars, and brick fireplaces for preparing tea. Their clothing was a mix of Chinese and Mongolian styles, with men wearing long coats, fur coats, and Chinese caps, while women's dresses resembled those of men but with some Chinese influences. The women's head dresses were particularly distinctive, featuring long strips of cloth, copper rings, and metal ornaments. The Yögur people had limited clothing and no holiday attire, making it difficult to collect ethnographic items as they only sold old, worn-out items. Their main handicrafts included weaving, basket-making, and knitting, with women weaving cloth on primitive looms and men making baskets and knitting stockings.
